          "body": "The appearance of the hand in 5:5 is the chapter's theological hinge. The fingers of a human hand (*etsba enash yad*) emerge and write on the plaster of the palace wall opposite the lampstand — in full view of the king. The lampstand's detail is not incidental: the feast was brilliantly lit for celebration, and the divine writing appears in the most visible, illuminated spot in the room. There is no ambiguity about whether the king saw it; 5:5 specifies that he 'saw the back of the hand that did the writing.' Belshazzar's physical response is described with clinical precision (5:6): his face grew pale, his thoughts alarmed him, his hip joints went slack, and his knees knocked together. This is the collapse of imperial composure. The man who had just performed a liturgy of triumph against Israel's God is reduced to physical terror by a hand. The whole apparatus of Babylonian wisdom — conjurers, Chaldeans, diviners (5:7) — fails completely. The inscription defeats every human interpretive system, demonstrating what Daniel will make explicit: the knowledge of what God has written belongs to God alone to reveal."
