          "body": "Daniel's speech (5:17-28) is one of the most concentrated pieces of prophetic prosecution in the Hebrew Bible. He begins not with the inscription but with Nebuchadnezzar — three verses (5:18-21) establishing the theological premise through historical narration. The Most High gave sovereignty; pride brought deposition; deposition ended when Nebuchadnezzar acknowledged that the Most High rules. This is not background information. It is the evidence that makes Belshazzar's guilt aggravated rather than simple. The pivot comes at 5:22: 'Yet you, his son, Belshazzar, have not humbled your heart, even though you knew all this.' The phrase 'even though you knew' is the moral crux of the chapter. Belshazzar's sin is not ignorance — it is informed rebellion. He had access to the most dramatic piece of theological evidence in the empire's recent history (Nebuchadnezzar's public confession, 4:34-37) and chose the opposite posture. As D.A. Carson notes in his work on divine sovereignty and human responsibility, the consistent biblical pattern is that greater light produces greater accountability — and here Belshazzar's accountability is absolute."
