          "body": "Verse 30 is one of the most terse verdict-executions in Scripture: 'That same night Belshazzar the Chaldean king was slain.' The chapter allows no interval. No repentance is offered; no delay is granted. This stands in deliberate contrast with Nebuchadnezzar, who received a twelve-month warning before his madness fell (4:29), seven years of discipline, and eventual restoration. Belshazzar received the inscription during the feast and was dead before dawn. Theologians in the Reformed tradition have pointed here to the doctrine of divine longsuffering: God's patience has limits, and when the time for response has passed — when knowledge is received and deliberately defied — judgment can be immediate. Jonathan Edwards's language about the precarious nature of the unrepentant sinner's position finds its narrative illustration here: Belshazzar was feasting on borrowed time that God had already recalled. The chapter closes in 5:31 with breathtaking simplicity: 'Darius the Mede received the kingdom.' The empire Belshazzar used temple vessels to celebrate changes hands in a single sentence. Human kingdoms are held in trust, not in fee simple."
