        "excerpt": "They drank the wine and praised the gods of gold and silver, of bronze, iron, wood and stone.",
        "body": "The opening four verses of Daniel 5 are not merely scene-setting; they constitute the chapter's thesis-act. Belshazzar's feast is an act of imperial theology. By commanding that the sacred vessels from Jerusalem's temple be used for wine-drinking while praising Babylonian idols, Belshazzar performs a liturgy whose message is explicit: the God of Israel has been defeated, His sacred objects belong to Babylon's gods, and the Babylonian king rules without accountability.\n\nThis act must be read against the immediate background of chapters 1 and 4. In 1:2, Nebuchadnezzar placed the Jerusalem temple vessels in the treasury of his own god (*beit elohav*) — a recognition, however distorted, that these were sacred objects belonging to a real deity. He never drank from them. Belshazzar escalates the provocation from trophy-keeping to active desecration. In chapter 4, Nebuchadnezzar had already been publicly humbled and had publicly confessed the Most High God (4:34-37). Belshazzar's feast occurs after that confession is on the record. The sacrilege is therefore not committed in ignorance of Israel's God; it is committed in studied contempt of Him.\n\nThe list of materials in 5:4 — gold, silver, bronze, iron, wood, and stone — is the same list that appears in the idol Nebuchadnezzar erected in chapter 3 and in the composite statue of chapter 2. The repetition is not accidental. Daniel is drawing a line of connection: Babylon's emperors have consistently attempted to secure divine legitimacy through manufactured objects. Each attempt has been or will be exposed as hollow. The gods of gold and silver 'do not see, hear, or understand' (5:23) — a phrase that echoes Psalm 115:5-7 and Isaiah 44:18 and frames Babylonian religion as the paradigm of human self-deception.\n\nThe key interpretive question is why the desecration of vessels triggers the divine response rather than, say, Belshazzar's general idolatry. The answer lies in the vessels' function as covenantal objects. They were instruments of Yahweh's worship — made to carry the sacrificial and liturgical service by which Israel maintained covenant relationship with God. To press them into service for idol-worship was not merely vandalism; it was a direct assault on the covenantal order. Calvin's comment on this passage notes that God 'permitted the vessels to be carried off as a token of the victory of the Babylonian gods, but He did not permit them to be profaned with impunity.'\n\n> **Aramaic note.** *Man* (vessels, 5:2-3) — implements, utensils, sacred articles. *Shevach* (praised, 5:4) — to laud, to give glory; the same root used in 4:34 when Nebuchadnezzar praises the Most High. The irony is precise: the same praise-vocabulary applied to the living God in chapter 4 is applied to lifeless idols in chapter 5."
